# Data Structures and Algorithms

## Choose the right data structure — always justify the choice

```go
// Lookup by unique key (agent by ID): map[uuid.UUID]AgentRecord — O(1)
// Ordered iteration (memories by score): sorted slice or heap — O(n log n) sort once
// Membership testing (is this token revoked?): Redis Bloom filter — O(1) probabilistic
// Range queries (sessions started between T1 and T2): B-Tree index in Postgres
// Vector similarity search (top-K memories by embedding): IVFFlat index in pgvector — O(n/lists)
// Queue with at-least-once delivery: Redis Streams (not channels, not list)
// LRU cache: container/list + map (Go), functools.lru_cache (Python)
```

## Complexity awareness for hot-path code

Always state the time and space complexity of any non-trivial algorithm.

```go
// GetTopMemories retrieves the k most relevant memories for an agent.
// Time: O(n log k) where n = total memories, k = requested count.
//       Uses a min-heap of size k; does not sort all n memories.
// Space: O(k) for the heap.
// If n > 10_000, this query is served from the IVFFlat index (O(n/lists) ANN).
func GetTopMemories(ctx context.Context, agentID uuid.UUID, k int) ([]Memory, error) { ... }
```

## Never use O(n²) when O(n log n) or O(n) is available

```go
// WRONG — O(n²): checking every pair for duplicates
for i, m1 := range memories {
    for j, m2 := range memories {
        if i != j && m1.ContentHash == m2.ContentHash { deduplicate(i, j) }
    }
}

// RIGHT — O(n): hash set for duplicate detection
seen := make(map[string]int, len(memories)) // pre-allocate
for i, m := range memories {
    if existing, ok := seen[m.ContentHash]; ok {
        deduplicate(existing, i)
    }
    seen[m.ContentHash] = i
}
```

## Use sets for membership, maps for association, slices for ordered sequences

```go
// WRONG — using slice for membership testing: O(n) per lookup
validStatuses := []string{"active", "paused", "suspended", "archived"}
func isValid(s string) bool {
    for _, v := range validStatuses { if v == s { return true } }
    return false
}

// RIGHT — map for O(1) lookup
var validStatuses = map[string]bool{
    "active": true, "paused": true, "suspended": true, "archived": true,
}
func isValid(s string) bool { return validStatuses[s] }
```

## Pre-allocate when cardinality is known

```go
// When the number of elements is known at collection time:
memories := make([]Memory, 0, totalCount)  // one allocation
ids := make(map[uuid.UUID]bool, len(rows)) // one allocation
```

## Prefer immutable data structures for cached objects

Objects stored in Redis or in-process caches must be treated as immutable after insertion. Mutating a cached object (slice append, map write) causes bugs when the same pointer is shared.

```go
// WRONG — mutates the cached object
cached := cache.Get(agentID)
cached.Tags = append(cached.Tags, "new-tag") // modifies cache!

// RIGHT — copy before mutation
cached := cache.Get(agentID)
updated := *cached // shallow copy of struct
updated.Tags = append(slices.Clone(cached.Tags), "new-tag")
cache.Set(agentID, &updated)
```
